thread.title: Major flooding in Coos County causes road closures, drowned farm lands and closed parks
thread.title_full: Major flooding in Coos County causes road closures, drowned farm lands and closed parks

author: Lexi Ryan & KCBY.com Staff
title: Major flooding in Coos County causes road closures, drowned farm lands and closed parks
text: Coos County is experiencing major flooding, with road closures, drowned farmlands and public parks closing throughout county, causing some vehicles to be swept away. Coos Bay police helped move traffic along Thursday due to dangerously high water levels on the roadways. \"The roadway is flooded up over the sidewalks and cars are beginning to float, so we’re shutting down the roadway,” Sgt. Gary Vrooman with CBPD said. “There’s a lot of flooding around town. We just ask that they be patient with their fellow drivers and watch their speed.” Coos Bay resident Tim Sanfelice said he has lived in Coos County for 13 years and has never seen flooding this bad. “The water in Lower Empire Lake was so high it was overflowing, it was so high that it eroded the road away [and] the dam,” he said “Then it flooded downstream at North Morrison street and they had to put road blocks there so cars wouldn’t go through it. We’re lucky the water didn’t get so high that it flooded my home and my neighbor’s homes.” Major flooding could be seen along Highway 42 in Coquille, with many farm lands underwater. According to our station's Chief Meteorologist John Mayer, the heaviest rainfall is expected Thursday night into early Friday morning, with approximately 1.5 inches of rainfall during that period. Resients should be aware of high water levels on roads, possible debris slides and rock falls, as well as gusty winds, Mayer said. The Coquille River has a flood warning in effect until Monday and the river is set to crest Saturday night into Sunday morning.
